"Nicolas D., Chaalali A., Drouineau H., Lobry J., Uriarte A., Borja A., Boët P.","Impact of global warming on European tidal estuaries: Some evidence of northward migration of estuarine fish species",2011,"Regional Environmental Change","11","3",,"639","649",,,10.1007/s10113-010-0196-3,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80052037585&partnerID=40&md5=799f7fd4b66ca5c083184d8328ed3c0a","Cemagref, UR EPBX, 50 av. de Verdun, 33612 Cestas, France; Marine Research Division, AZTI-Tecnalia, Pasaia, Spain","Nicolas, D., Cemagref, UR EPBX, 50 av. de Verdun, 33612 Cestas, France; Chaalali, A., Cemagref, UR EPBX, 50 av. de Verdun, 33612 Cestas, France; Drouineau, H., Cemagref, UR EPBX, 50 av. de Verdun, 33612 Cestas, France; Lobry, J., Cemagref, UR EPBX, 50 av. de Verdun, 33612 Cestas, France; Uriarte, A., Marine Research Division, AZTI-Tecnalia, Pasaia, Spain; Borja, A., Marine Research Division, AZTI-Tecnalia, Pasaia, Spain; Boët, P., Cemagref, UR EPBX, 50 av. de Verdun, 33612 Cestas, France","The aim of this study was to determine whether the latitudinal distribution of fish species that use estuaries to complete their entire life cycle has shifted northward as an expected consequence of global warming. The mean latitude of past fish species distributions found in 1970s' literature was compared with the mean latitude of distributions today based on fish density indices collected in 55 tidal estuaries along the Atlantic European seaboard, from Portugal to Scotland. Among the 15 most common species, 11 displayed a positive difference between current and past mean latitudes suggesting a northward shift of the populations. Using the occurrence of subtropical species in temperate areas as an indicator of water warming, the northernmost range limit of 10 subtropical species was subsequently focused on. Six of them were recorded up to their past northern latitudinal limit. These results reinforced the idea that a number of fish species associated to estuaries have migrated northwards over the last 30 years, possibly due to water warming. These ecological changes can get important managerial implications, i. e. in the assessment of the ecological status in European directives. © 2010 Springer-Verlag.","European tidal estuaries; Fish species; Global warming; Latitudinal shift",,,,,,,"Able, K.W., A re-examination of fish estuarine dependance: evidence for connectivity between estuarine and ocean habitats (2005) Estuar Coast Shelf Sci, 64, pp. 5-17; Beck, M.W., Heck, K.L., Able, K.W., Childers, D.L., Eggleston, D.B., Gillanders, B.M., Halpern, B., Weinstein, M.R., The identification, conservation, and management of estuarine and marine nurseries for fish and invertebrates (2001) Bioscience, 51, pp. 633-641; Blaber, S.J.M., Blaber, T.G., Factors affecting the distribution of juvenile estuarine and inshore fish (1980) J Fish Biol, 17, pp. 143-162; Brander, K., Blom, G., Borges, M.F., Erzini, K., Henderson, G., Mackenzie, B.R., Mendes, H., Toresen, R., Changes in fish distribution in the eastern North Atlantic: Are we seeing a coherent response to changing temperature? (2003) ICES Marine Science Symposia, 219, pp. 261-270; Breine, J., Quataert, P., Stevens, M., Ollevier, F., Volckaert, F.A.M., van den Bergh, E., Maes, J., A zone-specific fish-based biotic index as a management tool for the Zeeschelde estuary (Belgium) (2010) Mar Pollut Bull, 60, pp. 1099-1112; Cabral, H.N., Costa, M.J., Salgado, J.P., Does the Tagus estuary fish community reflect environmental changes? (2001) Clim Res, 18, pp. 119-126; Chassot, E., Mélin, F., Le Pape, O., Gascuel, D., Bottom-up control regulates fisheries production at the scale of eco-regions in European seas (2007) Mar Ecol Prog Ser, 343, pp. 45-55; Cheung, W.W.L., Lam, V.W.Y., Sarmiento, J.L., Kearney, K., Watson, R., Pauly, D., Projecting global marine biodiversity impacts under climate change scenarios (2009) Fish Fisheries, 10, pp. 235-251; Cheung, W.W.L., Lam, V.W.Y., Sarmiento, J.L., Kearney, 